James inquired about lesser-known temperature units, leading to the discovery of Rankine, Delisle, Réaumur, Rømer, and Newton scales. This exploration highlighted historical diversity in temperature measurement. Subsequently, James sought non-standard units for mass akin to "work days" for time. The discussion unveiled units like slugs, poundals, carats, quarters, kille, stones, and catties, showcasing diverse perspectives on mass measurement in various industries and regions.
